                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100111">France</placeName>
                                    <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100064">Paris</placeName>
                                </origPlace>, <origDate notAfter="1460" notBefore="1440">1440-1460</origDate>. The calendar is a so-called "composite" calendar typical of 15th-century Paris (see <ref target="http://manuscripts.org.uk/chd.dk/cals/pariscal.html">Erik Drigsdahl 1995</ref>) recording (at least) one feast for each day of the year. The style of the decorations and miniatures also place the manuscript in mid-15th-century Paris, albeit with one additional miniature on <locus from="31v" to="31v" scheme="folios"/> added in the 16th century.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>For several decades, at least, the manuscript was in the possession of the de Brunfay family, which seems to have had its origins around the area of <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100292">Vieux-Campagne</placeName>, just southeast of Paris <!--they appear to have been lords of, among other places, Quincy and Fontenailles -->(see <bibl>
                                    <title type="uniform" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107385">Annales de la Société historique &amp; archéologique du Gatinais: Tome 26</title>
                                    <citedRange from="267" to="269" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>). On <locus from="219r" to="220v" scheme="folios"/> is found a genealogy of the family written by a certain André de Brunfay. The earliest date he records is <date when="1530"/> (the birth of his (presumably) eldest son), and he signs his notes on July 14, <date when="1560"/> (<locus from="220v" to="220v" scheme="folios"/>: <quote>escript de ma mayn le dymenche xiiii de Juyllet V<hi rend="super">c</hi> lx</quote>). At least three later hands have added entries for <date when="1562">1562 </date> (the battle of Dreux; <locus from="219v" to="219v" scheme="folios"/>), <date when="1565"/> (the siege of Malta; <locus from="220r" to="220r" scheme="folios"/>), <date when="1598"/> (<locus from="219v" to="219v" scheme="folios"/>), <date when="1609"/> (<locus from="220r" to="220r" scheme="folios"/>), and <date when="1616"/> (<locus from="220v" to="220v" scheme="folios"/>), which is the latest date entered. There is no mention in the genealogy of a Katherine de Brunfay
                                - i.e. the former owner portrayed on <locus from="31v" to="31v" scheme="folios"/> - but André's son Jacques (mentioned) is recorded to have had a daughter by that name, who married in 1599 (see <bibl>
                                    <title type="uniform" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107385">Annales de la Société historique &amp; archéologique du Gatinais: Tome 26</title>
                                    <citedRange from="269" to="269" unit="page">Note 1.</citedRange>
                                </bibl>).</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>An owner's note in an early modern hand on <locus from="1r" to="1r" scheme="folios"/> states that the book belonged to a <quote>mademoyselle de cheurieres</quote>, probably designating <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100302">Chevrières</placeName>. Next to it, an owner's note in a different hand gives the name <quote>Marguerit<supplied reason="damage">e</supplied> de Bielzuiais</quote>, probably designating <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100303">Beauvais</placeName>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The watermark on <locus from="SR1" to="SR1" scheme="folios"/>, added at rebinding, gives the name <quote>Wunnerlich</quote> (first initial(s) not visible); Piccard online identifies a similar watermark belonging to Johann Albrecht Wunnerlich, active in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100310">Hof</placeName>
                                <date from="1746" to="1822">1746–1822</date> (see <ref target="https://www.wasserzeichen-online.de/wzis/struktur.php?ref=DE3270-jurid387_III-wm1">Piccard online</ref>). A family of Wunnerlichs appear as papermakers in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100311">Bavaria</placeName> (<placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100310">Hof</placeName>/<placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100309">Moschendorf</placeName>) between <date when="1693"/> and <date when="1856"/> (see <ref target="https://www.blogus.de/Pmnamen.html#W">blogus</ref>).</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>A dedication in Polish on <locus from="SL2" to="SL2" scheme="folios"/> reveals that the manuscript was given to the <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102658">countess von Engeström</persName> (Rosalie, née Drya-Chlapowska), wife of statesman <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/101133">Lars von Engeström</persName> (<date from="1751" to="1826">1751–1826</date>), by <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/102657">Felix Biernacki</persName>, a friend of the von Engeström family, with gratitude for meetings in <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100078">Stockholm </placeName> and <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100291">Warsaw</placeName>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>The signa <quote>D. B. IV. 5</quote> and <quote>50</quote> on <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/> have not been identified.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>The manuscript was part of the donation to the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">National Library</orgName> of <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/101133"> Lars von Engeström</persName>'s personal library made in <date when="1864"/> by von Engeström's grandson (see <ref target="https://sok.riksarkivet.se/sbl/artikel/16158">SBL</ref>).</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
